84. 27. una totius caeli conversione cursus astrorum dispares. The stars have an apparent motion with the whole heavcns around the earth, but not all at the same rate. The greater part of them move so that they always keep the same place in the heavens, thus moving only along with the heavens, and these are called stellae fixac,· others move in such manner that while moving along with the heavens around the earth they have an independent motion of their own, and are seen nowhere and now there 3 they are therefore called planctae. But these cursus dispares also sollow an established law; hence the expression conservari. Comp. c. 20, 51·
